{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509184"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:14:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11400"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11400"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.03,0.02,0.03,0.76]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4036"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111192"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4036"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11400"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93319"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"101"},{"type":"tags","id":"2664"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42586"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111192"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with an eight-month history of progressively worsening shortness of breath on exertion and reduced exercise tolerance. In the past two months, he has also experienced dizziness, particularly whilst walking his dog. His medical history includes hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and chronic kidney disease. His medications include amlodipine, atorvastatin, metformin, and perindopril. He has a 50 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min and regular, blood pressure 167/94 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. On auscultation, there is an ejection systolic murmur heard maximally at the second intercostal space at the right sternal border, with a soft S2. The murmur radiates to the carotids.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely valvular pathology present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Non-severe aortic stenosis","Severe mitral regurgitation","Non-severe mitral regurgitation","Mixed aortic valve disease","Severe aortic stenosis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms of aortic stenosis including exertional dyspnoea, reduced exercise tolerance, and dizziness. The examination findings of an ejection systolic murmur at the right upper sternal border radiating to the carotids are typical of aortic stenosis. The key finding that distinguishes severity is the soft S2, which is one of the most specific clinical signs of severe aortic stenosis. In severe disease, the valve leaflets become so stiff and immobile that they fail to close forcefully, resulting in a diminished S2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevere aortic stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct diagnosis based on the combination of progressive symptoms (dyspnoea and dizziness) and the soft S2. Other features that would support severe stenosis include a late-peaking murmur, slow-rising pulse (pulsus parvus et tardus), and signs of heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-severe aortic stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with a preserved or normal S2, and symptoms would be less pronounced. The murmur in mild to moderate stenosis tends to peak earlier in systole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevere mitral regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E would produce a holosystolic murmur best heard at the apex, radiating to the axilla. The primary murmur characteristics and location in this case are consistent with aortic stenosis rather than mitral regurgitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-severe mitral regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E would similarly present with an apical holosystolic murmur but would be unlikely to cause the degree of symptoms described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed aortic valve disease\u003C/strong\u003E (combined stenosis and regurgitation) would typically include an additional diastolic murmur from the aortic regurgitation component, which is not described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEchocardiography with careful Doppler assessment of trans-aortic gradient is the clinical standard for quantitation of aortic stenosis, with severity being AVA \u0026lt;1.0 cm2 by current guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A soft S2 is the most specific clinical sign of severe aortic stenosis.","Late-peaking systolic murmur, slow-rising pulse, and signs of heart failure also suggest severe aortic stenosis.","The classic radiation pattern of aortic stenosis is to the carotid arteries."],"references":["Joseph J, Naqvi SY, Giri J, et al. Aortic Stenosis: Pathophysiology, Diagnosis, and Therapy. Am J Med. 2017; 130:253-63.","Talley NJ, O\u2019Connor S. Section 2: The cardiovascular system. In: Talley N, O\u2019Connor S, editors. Clinical Examination: a systematic guide to physical diagnosis. 9th ed. Chatswood (NSW): Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93319"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11400"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93319"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-10T14:08:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-10T14:08:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4036"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111192"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type"